1 Tidyverse

The tidyverse is a collection of R packages designed for data science. All packages share the same grammar and data structures. Therefore, they work well together as part of larger data analysis pipeline.

We can import data with readr or readxl, which we have already seen. Then organize it with tidyr, manipulate it and transform it with dplyr, visualized with ggplot2, and finally communicate our findings with RMarkdown.

Today we will dive into the two packages useful to work with data:

  • dplyr is a powerful package to manipulate, clean and summarize data.

  • tidyr enables you shifting between data formats.

Tomorrow we will be ready to jump into data visualization.

2 Manipulate data with dplyr

The package dplyr includes a set of functions that match the most common actions performed on a data set (select rows: filter (), select columns: select(), sort arrange(), transform or add new variables mutate(), summarize summarise()).

First, install and load tidyverse, dplyr will be installed within it.

install.packages("tidyverse",
                 repos = "http://cran.us.r-project.org") # install package
library(tidyverse) # load library

In order to carry out these actions we must take into account some common characteristics:

  • The first argument is always a data.frame or a tibble (modern data frame)
  • The rest of the arguments indicate the parameters that specify what we want to do
  • The result will always have a data frame or tibble structure

2.1 select()

It selects one or a set of columns.

For example, select columns nameand sleep_total from data set msleep.

select1 <- select(.data = msleep, # data set
                          name,   # 1st column to select
                          sleep_total) # 2nd column to select 

head(select1, # show result
     n = 2)   # only 2 rows

As in the previous example, we can select everything except a specific column using the - (subtraction) operator.

select2 <- select(.data = msleep, 
       -name)          # show everything except column name

head(select2,
     n = 2)

The operator : can be used to select a range of columns.

select3 <- select(.data = msleep, 
                          genus:order)  # select from genus to order

head(select3,
     n = 2)

2.2 filter()

This function allows us to select the rows that meet the conditions we specify.

For example, filter species that have more than 16 total hours of sleep:

filter1 <- filter(msleep, 
                  sleep_total > 16)

head(filter1,
     n = 2)

Filter those animals that have more than 16 total hours of sleep and have a body weight greater than 1 kg:

filter2 <- filter(msleep, 
                  sleep_total > 16, # 1st condition
                  bodywt > 1)       # 2nd condition

head(filter2,
     n = 2)

Now we want to filter animals that are of the order Primates or the order Perissodactyla:

filter3 <- filter(msleep, 
                  order == "primates" | order == "Perissodactyla") # condition
# The operator "|" means OR.                   

head(filter3,
     n = 2)

2.3 mutate()

The mutate function allows us to create new columns containing calculations from those we already have or to generate new columns.

For example, we can generate a new column called rem_ratio with the proportion of rem sleep over the total sleep hours.

# Specify the data set, then, the name of the new column and its calculation

mutate1 <- mutate(msleep, 
                  rem_ratio = sleep_rem / sleep_total)

head(mutate1,
     n = 5)

Several new columns can also be generated, separated by commas.

mutate2 <- mutate(msleep,
                  rem_proportion = sleep_rem / sleep_total, # 1st new column 
                  bodywt_gram = bodywt * 1000)              # 2nd new column

head(mutate2,
     n = 2)

With mutate, it is also possible to change the data type of each column. For example, change the column order from character to factor:

mutate3 <- mutate(msleep, 
                  order = factor(order)) # change the type of column to factor
head(mutate3,
     n = 2)

2.3.1 Modifications of mutate

Lets say we want to convert all the columns to factor:

mutate4 <- mutate_all(msleep,
                      as.factor) # convert all columns to factors
head(mutate4,
     n = 2)

We might be interested in applying logarithms only to those columns which are numeric. These operations could be done with the function mutate_if():

mutate5 <- mutate_if(msleep,      # data set
                     is.numeric,  # if is numeric, apply log function
                     log)    
head(mutate5, 
     n = 2 )

In a small data frame like the one we are using, we can directly indicate the columns on which we want to apply logarithms with mutate_at()

mutate6 <- mutate_at(msleep,                    # data set
                     c("sleep_total", "awake"), # only log in these two columns
                     log)    
head(mutate6, 
     n = 2 )

2.4 arrange()

The arrange function allows us to order the data according to the values of another variable.

If we want to show the values of our data set in order of the total number of hours of sleep, from lowest to highest:

arrange1 <- arrange(msleep, 
                    sleep_total) # variable to sort the rest of the data frame
head(arrange1,
     n = 5)

If you want to order from highest to lowest you must add the operator -

arrange2 <- arrange(msleep, 
                    -sleep_total) # from high to low
head(arrange2,
     n = 5)

It is also possible to order by characters:

arrange3 <- arrange(msleep, 
                    name) # sort alphabetically by name column
head(arrange3,
     n = 5)

2.5 pipes %>%

The %>% operator allows us to link functions without having to create variables for temporary use or without having to nest functions.

Dplyr imports this operator from another package (magrittr). In general, the operator allows us to link the result of a function to the input of another function.

For example, lets say we only want those mammals with a total sleep higher than 16 hours and belonging to the order Primates or Carnivora. In addition, all we need is their body weight and we want to display it sorted by weight (from low to high). This could be implemented as:

# First, filter the original data set to get only mammals with total sleep > 16h
msleep1 <- filter(msleep,           # data set to filter
                  sleep_total > 16) # condition for filtering

# Filter the latter object to get only mammals from orders Primates or Carnivora
msleep2 <- filter(msleep1,                          # data already filtered
                  order == "Primates" | order == "Carnivora") # Order has to be equal(==) to Primates or (|) Carnivora

# Extract only the column bodywt that meets all the above conditions
msleep3 <- select(msleep2,
                  bodywt)  # save only the column bodywt which meets the above conditions

# Sort the values from low to high bodywt
arrange(msleep3)

Or we could have nested in a single command:

arrange(select(filter(filter(msleep,              # sort the result 
                             sleep_total > 16),   # subset by total sleep > 16
                      order == "Primates" | order == "Carnivora"), # filter by order
               bodywt))                           # extract only column bodywt

Both approaches have their advantages. The first approach is easier to understand, and easier to track each step. The second approach takes up less space and avoids saving several objects in the intermediate steps.

The pipe operator is used to combine the best of the latter approaches. It is used to connect sentences. It takes the result from the first step and use it as the input for the function of the next step. We avoid having to save every step in an intermediate object but also the confusing grammar (e.g., multiple brackets) of nested functions.

Now, lets see how we can implement the pipe in our example:

msleep %>%        # initial data set, pipe it into the next step
  filter(sleep_total > 16) %>%  # filter the previous data set by sleep_total > 16
  filter(order == "Primates" | order == "Carnivora") %>% # filter the output from the previous step by order
  select(bodywt) %>% # extract column bodywt from the output of previous step
  arrange() # sort the result of the previous step

At the end of the day, what matters is that you are able to analyze your data and obtain trustful results in a fast and easy way. You can decide which approach to use, intermediate objects, nested functions or the pipe.

2.6 summarise()

The summarise() function allows us to create statistical summaries for our data from a given column. For this, we can use the already known functions, such as mean(), min(), max(), sd(),n(). For example:

msleep %>%                              # data set
  summarise(MEAN = mean(sleep_total),   # create a new column with the mean of sleep_total
            MINIMUM = min(sleep_total), # create a new column with the minimum of sleep_total
            MAXIMUM = max(sleep_total), # create a new column with the maximum of sleep_total
            N = n())                    # create a new column with the number of observations in the data set (rows)

2.7 Group operations using group_by()

The verb group_by() allows you to separate the table according to a variable and apply the summarise() function to each subset.

msleep %>%                              # data set
  group_by(order) %>%                   # group by variable order 
  summarise(MEAN = mean(sleep_total),   # create a new table and apply the following functions to each order
            StandardDeviation = sd(sleep_total), # save in a new column called "StandardDeviation" the sd() of each order
            N = n()) %>%    # number of observations in each order
            top_n(4)        # show only the first 4 rows

2.8 Joining data with dplyr

dplyrhas several functions to join two tables by a common variable.

With inner_join() a new table is generated which combines table A with table B based on a union variable by=, in this case is name.

inner_join(filter1,   # table that includes rows with  sleep_total > 16 
           filter2,   # table that includes rows with  sleep_total>16 & bodywt>1
           by="name") # union variable

Other options are left_join() or full_join(). Search their peculiarities with help().

Sometime what we want is to find the observations that are NOT common between tables, for this we use anti_join().

# Show me the names that do not match between tables. 
anti_join(filter1,    # table that includes rows with  sleep_total > 16 
           filter2,   # table that includes rows with  sleep_total>16 & bodywt>1
           by="name") # union variable

3 Rearrange a table with tidyr

The goal of tidyr is to help you create tidy data. Tidy data is data where:

  1. Every column is variable.
  2. Every row is an observation.
  3. Every cell is a single value.

It seems easy. Now look at this data frame that collects the number of insects captured each trap each year. Is it tidy?

# Data in wide format
d1 <- data.frame(trap = 1:10,
                 Year.2013 = c(12, 10, 5, 3, 15, 11, 12, 10, 7, 5),
                 Year.2014 = c(12, 3, 15, 1, 13, 4, 1, 16, 7, 13),
                 Year.2015 = c(12, 0, 5, 3, 15, 11, 12, 10, 7, 15),
                 Year.2016 = c(2, 10, 6, 3, 1, 11, 12, 10, 7, 10))
head (d1)

Of course NOT. Year should be a variable with its own column. Data should be given in this way:

# Data in long format 
d2 <- data.frame(trap = rep(1:10, 4),
                 year = factor(c(rep("Year.2013", 10), 
                                 rep("Year.2014", 10), 
                                 rep("Year.2015", 10), 
                                 rep("Year.2016", 10))),
                 numberInsects = c(12, 10, 5, 3, 15, 11, 12, 10, 7, 5,
                                   12, 3, 15, 1, 13, 4, 1, 16, 7, 13,
                                   12, 0, 5, 3, 15, 11, 12, 10, 7, 15,
                                   2, 10, 6, 3, 1, 11, 12, 10, 7, 10))
head(d2)

We can convert data from the wide to the long format and viceversa by pivotting.

3.1 From wide to long pivot_longer()

d1.long <- pivot_longer(data = d1,  # data in the wide format
                        cols = Year.2013:Year.2016, # columns to pivot into the long format
                        names_to = "Year",          # name of the column to create from the data stored in the column names of data.     
                        values_to = "insects")      # name of the column to create from the data stored in cell values 
head(d1.long)

3.2 From long to wide pivot_wider()

d2.wide <- pivot_wider(data = d2,  # data in the long format
                       names_from = year,          # column to get the name of the output columns  
                       values_from = numberInsects)# column to get the cell values from  
head(d2.wide)
